## Principles

**Tests first when an oracle exists.** If there is a known-good reference — published DFT data, experimental measurements, a higher-level method, a benchmark dataset — the test harness is the most valuable artefact you produce. Write the test (what the oracle says) before the implementation. When you find a bug, reproduce it as a failing test before fixing. The harness is what lets you bisect the pipeline when something disagrees.

**Concise test output.** Every line of noisy test output displaces useful context. On success, print at most a few lines. On failure, print: max relative error, the index or input where it occurs, and the overall pass rate — never raw arrays. Verbose diagnostics (full residuals, intermediate fields, dumped trajectories) go to `test_logs/` files, not stdout. Make assert messages greppable so `grep ERROR test_logs/*.log` finds them.

Good: `FAILED test_logp — max err 0.032 at idx 17 (49/50 pass <0.1)`
Bad:  `FAILED — arrays not equal: [1.83e-4, 1.82e-4, ...] (500 more lines)`

**`--fast` mode by default during development.** The default dev cycle is `pytest -q --fast` after every change; the full suite only before commit. Fast mode runs a deterministic ~10% subsample (every 10th molecule, every 10th frame, 5 of 150 k-modes). It catches the same regressions in seconds instead of minutes, so the iteration loop stays short enough to think in.

**`docs/progress.md` is shared memory.** Each session starts in a fresh context. `docs/progress.md` is how the next session — or the next agent — orients. Update after every meaningful unit of work. Record dated completions (`2026-05-28 background: 25/25`), what's blocked, and especially **failed approaches** (`Tried Tsit5 — too stiff. Switched to Kvaerno5.`) so they aren't re-attempted. Track suite pass rates over time so regressions are visible.

**No fudge factors.** If a test fails with a 0.2% error, there is a missing term — a wrong sign, a wrong factor, a missing summation, a stale index. Find the actual bug. Do not multiply by 1.002 or add a constant offset to make the test pass. If you are tempted, the discrepancy is not yet isolated; bisect further upstream.

**Small commits.** One thing per commit: one function, one module, one bugfix. Each commit passes all existing tests and includes tests for the new code. Refactors go in their own commits, separate from features, so reviewers (and your future self) can understand each change in isolation. Run `pytest -q --fast` before every commit; never "fix it later."

**Document for the next session, not for users.** Documentation is a coordination mechanism, not a deliverable. Every module docstring explains: what it does, what it takes and returns (types and shapes), any non-obvious numerical choices and why, and known limitations. When the project has an oracle, name the reference function or equation each module mirrors (`file.c:5070`, paper Eq. 12) so terms can be reviewed against the source.

