## Coding style

**Pure functions where reasonable.** No mutable globals, no hidden side effects. Pure functions compose, test cleanly, and parallelise trivially. Exceptions exist (caches, parallel I/O) but should be named explicitly, not hidden inside an otherwise pure-looking call.

**Full type hints on public functions, including return type.** The signature is the cheapest, most-read documentation in the codebase; missing return types make every caller speculate. Centralise complex aliases in `src/{{PKG}}/typeshed.py` so consumers can `from {{PKG}}.typeshed import …` instead of duplicating definitions.

**Bundle results as frozen dataclasses.** Not loose tuples or dicts. `@dataclass(frozen=True)` (or `pydantic.BaseModel(frozen=True)`) makes results self-documenting — every consumer sees field names and types — and kills the "which index was energy again?" bug.

**Implement modules in dependency order.** Each new module should depend only on those already written. List the order in `docs/specs/` or near the top of `DESIGN.md` if you have one. Build bottom-up; when you find yourself wanting to import from a not-yet-written module, write that one first.

**Units explicit.** Embed units in names (`energy_kcal_mol`, `r_angstrom`, `t_fs`) or in the dataclass field. Convert at boundaries, never in the middle. Random seeds are fixed in any script that draws randomness, and the seed is stored alongside the output.

**SMILES flat unless stereo is the point.** Strip `/`, `\`, `@` for downstream structure handling; reintroduce stereo only at the step that needs it. See the `authoring-smiles` skill.

**Every line earns its place.** No prose padding. If a comment restates the code, delete the comment or rewrite the code. Match the surrounding idiom rather than inventing a new one.

